#. type: Title ###
#: docs/admin/30.apps/index.mdx:43
#, no-wrap
msgid "Subpaths vs. individual domains per apps"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/30.apps/index.mdx:46
#, no-wrap
msgid "Among specific questions, forms usually ask you to choose a domain and a path onto which the app will be accessible.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/30.apps/index.mdx:48
#, no-wrap
msgid "In the context of YunoHost, it is quite common to have a single (or a few) domains on which several apps are installed in \"subpaths\", so that you end up with something like this:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/30.apps/index.mdx:58
#, no-wrap
msgid "Alternatively, you may choose to install each (or some) apps on a dedicated domain. Beyond the aesthetic, using sub-domains instead of sub-paths allows the possibility to move a service to another server more easily. Also, some applications may need an entire domain dedicated to them, for technical reasons. The disadvantage is that you have to add a new domain each time, and therefore potentially configure additional DNS records, restart the diagnostics and install a new Let's Encrypt certificate.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/30.apps/index.mdx:60
#, no-wrap
msgid "This might look prettier for end users, but is generally considered more complicated and less efficient in the context of YunoHost, since you need to add a new domain each time. Nevertheless, some apps might need an entire domain dedicated to them, for technical reasons.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/30.apps/index.mdx:62
#, no-wrap
msgid "If all apps from the previous example were installed on a separate domain, this would give something like this:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced div block (info)
#: docs/admin/30.apps/index.mdx:70
#, no-wrap
msgid "Many applications integrate a feature that allows you to change the URL of your application. This choice between subpath and subdomain can be reversed in some cases via a simple manipulation in the administration interface.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: docs/admin/30.apps/index.mdx:74
#, no-wrap
msgid "User access management and public apps"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/30.apps/index.mdx:77
#, no-wrap
msgid "The installation form usually asks whether or not the app should be publically accessible. If you choose to not make it public, only users logged in YunoHost will be able to reach it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced div block (tip)
#: docs/admin/30.apps/index.mdx:78
#, no-wrap
msgid "After installation, this can be configured via the webadmin in the [Groups and permissions panel](/admin/users/groups_and_permissions), or similarly via the command-line subcategory `yunohost user permission`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: docs/admin/30.apps/index.mdx:82
#, no-wrap
msgid "Instructions after installation"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/30.apps/index.mdx:85
#, no-wrap
msgid "Some applications need to give you instructions, URLs or credentials once they are installed. So remember to check the email of the first user account or the admin user selected before installation, if it was prompted.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: docs/admin/30.apps/index.mdx:86
#, no-wrap
msgid "Multi-instance applications"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/30.apps/index.mdx:89
#, no-wrap
msgid "Some applications support the ability to be installed several times (at different locations) ! To do so, just go another time in <HighlightApplications/> ‚Üí <HighlightAppInstall/>, and select again the application to install.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: docs/admin/30.apps/index.mdx:90
#, no-wrap
msgid "LDAP / SSO integration"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/30.apps/index.mdx:93
#, no-wrap
msgid "Applications that allow users to register may support integration with the LDAP / Single Sign On of YunoHost, so that users who connect to the user portal can be automatically logged in all these apps.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/30.apps/index.mdx:95
#, no-wrap
msgid "However, some applications do not support this as it can be either not implemented in the upstream, or the package does not work on this part yet. This information is usually available on the README of the application package.\n"
msgstr ""

